# Data Lake Operational Metrics \- Design

This document explores the possible designs that would enable Polaris to collect and serve Data Lake operational metrics to external systems.

## Metrics computation component

### Main features

A new component dedicated to building operational metrics would be added to the codebase.  This component would be responsible for:

1. Computing the new operational metrics of a given entity, by scanning all the Iceberg Metadata available on the Block Storage layer  
2. Updating the already existing metrics after each table/view commit or refresh performed by Polaris, leveraging the Events API  
3. Update the already existing metrics of a given entity after a user request  
4. Storing those metrics in the MetaStore

A new API would be added to Polaris to allow external systems to query the metrics collected for a given entity.  This would be a 100% read API.  I.e. external systems may not be able to add arbitrary values to metrics or delete the metrics maintained by Polaris.

The rest of this section describes the reasons why each of those major features are necessary.

#### Computing metrics using all metadata

This operation is needed the first time metrics are built for a given entity.  It is necessary to build the first values that can then be updated incrementally.

This operation can involve a substantial amount of I/O, for large tables.  So the metrics component needs to be configurable so that these operations do not starve the server from critical resources (e.g. CPU).

Possible approaches to limit the impact on other Polaris activities include limiting the number of threads that can perform metrics computation and splitting a computation into multiple smaller tasks.

#### Update existing metrics after certain events

This operation is needed so that Polaris can achieve metrics accuracy.  Leveraging the existing Events API, it is possible to be notified whenever a Polaris instance has performed a commit/refreshed a table/view.

By computing the difference in metric values since the last computation, the metrics component can rebuild metric accuracy without having to rescan the entirety of metadata for that particular entity.

Note that this feature does *not* guarantee perfect accuracy, especially in the context of multi-node deployments.

#### Update existing metrics after user trigger

This is really a duplication of the previous section.  Except that the trigger for a metrics refresh is a user action.  This operation is needed to guarantee that a user gets the most up-to-date value for a given metrics.

Some users (e.g. Table Maintenance Systems) may not need perfect accuracy.  But some other use cases could require that the metrics are as up to date as possible.  This is why a user triggered metrics refresh is necessary.

#### Store metrics in the MetaStore

Although the memory requirements for all operational metrics of a given table should be quite low, we need to consider the number of tables and views across all realms served by a given Polaris instance.  Especially in the context of a multi-tenant Polaris deployment, as well as for a single-tenant deployment where the Data Lake is especially large.

In order to strictly limit the amount of heap that the metrics component will use, the metrics themselves will be persisted to the MetaStore.  They will be loaded on-demand for each user read request or recomputation.

Note that depending on the specific implementation, it would be possible to allow the EntityCache to keep those metrics in memory for a certain amount of time.  However, at the time of writing, there is no clear time locality in metrics that would make them good candidates for caching.

### API

New API endpoints will be added to allow external systems to fetch the operational metrics associated with a given entity.  In order to distinguish the new API from the Iceberg REST API , while maintaining consistency, all new endpoints will be located under `/api/operational-metrics`.

#### Get a given metric for a specific table

| Endpoint | `/v1/{prefix}/namespaces/{namespace}/tables/{table}/metrics/{metric}` |
| :---- | :---- |
| **Method** | GET |
| **Summary** | Fetch a given operational metrics associated with a given table. |
| **Parameters** | (Optional) A boolean parameter to request metrics to be refreshed before being returned.  Default: `false`. (Optional) A list of percentiles to return, if the metric is a histogram, where each value is a double.  Example: `0.90` denotes the 90th percentile.  Default: `[0, 0.1, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 0.90, 1]`. |
| **Response** | A `200` status response with a json-encoded object if the operation is successful.  |

The response is a JSON object whose body contains the metric name, and value(s).  The following are examples of valid responses:

```json
{
  "last-updated-timestamp", 1756827441,
    "metric": {
      "type": "point",
      "value": 14827
    }
}
```

```json
{
  "last-updated-timestamp", 1756827441,
    "metric": {
      "type": "histogram",
      "percentiles": {
        "0": 49,
        "0.1": 73,
        "0.25": 145,
        "0.5": 521,
        "0.75": 1024,
        "0.9": 6930,
        "1": 6955
      }
    }
}
```

#### Get all metrics of a given table

| Endpoint | `/v1/{prefix}/namespaces/{namespace}/tables/{table}` |
| :---- | :---- |
| **Method** | GET |
| **Summary** | Fetch all the operational metrics associated with a given table. |
| **Parameters** | (Optional) A boolean parameter to request metrics to be refreshed before being returned.  Default: `false`. (Optional) A list of percentiles to return, if the metric is a histogram, where each value is a double.  Example: `0.90` denotes the 90th percentile.  Default: `[0, 0.1, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 0.90, 1]`. |
| **Response** | A `200` status response with a json-encoded object if the operation is successful.  |

The response is a JSON object whose body contains an array associating each metric name with its value(s).  The following is an example of a valid response:

```json
{
  "total-number-of-files": {
    "last-updated-timestamp": 1756827441,
    "metric": {
      "type": "point",
      "value": 14827
    }
  },
  "partition-sizes": {
    "last-updated-timestamp": 1756827441,
    "metric": {
      "type": "histogram",
      "percentiles": {
        "0": 49,
        "0.1": 73,
        "0.25": 145,
        "0.5": 521,
        "0.75": 1024,
        "0.9": 6930,
        "1": 6955
      }
    }
  }
}
```

#### Request metrics update for a given table

| Endpoint | `/v1/{prefix}/namespaces/{namespace}/tables/{table}` |
| :---- | :---- |
| **Method** | POST |
| **Summary** | Request all metrics of the given table to be updated. |
| **Parameters** | An Iceberg sequence number corresponding to the last known sequence number for that table. |
| **Response** | A `204` status response if the operation is successful.  |

## Threading

Metrics computation, when triggered by events, should be an asynchronous process.  If possible, it should even be a low-priority process, so that real-time user queries get priority over resources.

This section analyses the possible ways metrics computation could be executed.

In each case, any time a table/view is updated/refreshed, an event will be fired and trigger a metric computation operation.

### New TaskHandler

Polaris already has a way to execute background tasks, using the TaskExecutor thread pool.  It would be possible to compute metrics in a dedicated TaskHandler.  Any time a commit/refresh event is fired, we would schedule a new computation task.

#### Pros

* Reuse current thread pool and infrastructure  
* Less added code

#### Cons

* Worst case scenario: all task executor threads could be busy computing metrics  
* Worst case scenario: a metric is recomputed by multiple threads at the same time

### Hash-based thread pools partitioning

In this approach, a new thread pool would be created for metrics computations.  Its size would be fixed at Polaris startup time (taken from configuration).  Each time a new computation is scheduled, a hash is computed based on the targeted entity.   Then this hash is used to pick the thread responsible for the computation.

#### Pros

* Fixed resource usage (e.g. 32 threads total)  
* Serialization guarantees: metrics for a given table are always computed by the same thread, resulting in no concurrent computation of the same metrics  
* No starvation of existing task executor

#### Cons

* More code  
* An additional thread pool

### Recommendation

Assuming the ultimate goal is to have the least amount of impact on existing workloads, a hash-based thread pool partitioning model seems the more appropriate solution.

## Deployment options

### Option 1 \- Inside Polaris runtime

This deployment option is the simplest approach.  The new component dedicated for operational metrics computation is added to the existing Polaris runtime, along with its API endpoints.

#### ![][image1]

#### Pros

* Simplest approach  
* Requires the least amount of code change  
* Does not change Polaris deployment model

#### Cons

* The metrics computation overhead could impact the performance of Polaris user-facing endpoints.  
* If they are cached, the metrics would increase the pressure on the EntityCache and could result in more evictions.

### Option 2 \- Separate process

This deployment option consists in creating a separate runtime dedicated for operational metrics.  This runtime would be responsible for serving the operational metrics API queries as well as (re)computing them.  It would not share any logical resources with the main Polaris runtime (thread pools, handlers, connections to the MetaStore).

An event listener would be added in the current Polaris runtime to schedule metric refresh operations in the separate runtime.  As a result, the operational metrics runtime will need to be started before the main Polaris runtime, and a new configuration parameter will be added to Polaris so that the runtime knows the base URL of the operational metrics runtime.

![][image2]

#### Pros

* Best isolation (no thread pool or entity cache is shared between the two runtimes)  
* Clean separation between foreground-intensive tasks (Iceberg REST API) and background-intensive tasks (operational metrics computation)

#### Cons

* More complex deployment

## Data representation

### Point metrics

Certain metrics contain a single value (e.g. total number of files in a table, total number of partitions, â€¦).  For those metrics, the storage format as well as the API response format is trivial: it is composed of the metric name and its value, as well as the timestamp of the last metric update.

### Histograms

Histograms inherently require more than a single data point.  For those metrics, the storage format will be based on the HdrHistogram library.  This enables precise tracking on the whole histogram.

In terms of storage, the HdrHistogram instance will be serialized to a byte array and stored as-is in the MetaStore.  At histogram retrieval time, the requested percentiles will be extracted from the histogram and returned to the user.

## Data security considerations

Certain metrics depend on table data.  For example, per-partition metrics.  For those, the Operational Metrics component will need to store the partition key in the MetaStore.  This creates a security concern as the MetaStore may not necessarily be as secured as the underlying Block Storage layer.

To mitigate this issue, instead of indexing metrics per partition key, those metrics will be indexed using a hash (SHA-1) of the partition key.  This solves the security concern as it ensures that no table data is stored in the MetaStore.

The only downside is that certain partition keys may produce the same hash.  This could change the metric value and present a less accurate picture than the real table state.  However this is considered acceptable, considering the low collision likelihood.
